      <hedline>
        <hl1>Path to Peace, Through Jerusalem</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gerald Albert letter, commenting on July 20 article, says Jerusalem should be made an international city</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Clinton Leaves Peace Talks; Arafat and Barak Stay'' (front page, July 20):</p>
        <p>Ultimately, Israelis and Palestinians have to answer one question: Which is more important, the doctrinaire religious symbolism of Jerusalem as the capital of one or the other group, or the lives of thousands of their young people?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Clinton Leaves Peace Talks; Arafat and Barak Stay'' (front page, July 20):</p>
        <p>Ultimately, Israelis and Palestinians have to answer one question: Which is more important, the doctrinaire religious symbolism of Jerusalem as the capital of one or the other group, or the lives of thousands of their young people?</p>
        <p>The only solution seems to be acceptance of an international city, open to all. Otherwise history may record this as one more instance illustrating George Washington's observation: ''Religious controversies are always productive of more acrimony and irreconcilable hatreds than those which spring from any other cause.''</p>
        <p>GERALD ALBERT  East Meadow, N.Y., July 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
